Examining the impact of inequality on TFP requires TFP scores data as well as inequality indices. To obtain the TFP scores data, a growth accounting approach was used. This approach is most commonly employed in calculating TFP data at a macroeconomic level of analysis (Hall and Jones 1999; Kalio et al. 2012; Bilgic-Alpaslan 2015; Algarini 2017; Saad 2017). The calculation of TFP under a growth accounting approach requires data on output, physical capital, employment and labour compensation (wages). TFP is then obtained as a simple Solow residual (Solow 1956). Along the lines of the Solow-Swan model (see, for example, Barro and Sala-i-Martin 2004), we therefore specified a production function using the traditional Cobb–Douglas framework as follows:9\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
